		"notes": "This word is not listed in the Minecraft Official Glossary, so it is intended to be translated.<br><br>Most of the translations have borrowed this word unadapted; to name a few: Arabic&nbsp;Ø²ÙˆÙ…Ø¨ÙŠâ€&nbsp;<i>zÅ«mbÄ«</i>, Armenian&nbsp;Õ¦Õ¸Õ´Õ¢Õ«&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Azerbaijani&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Catalan&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, French&nbsp;<i>zombie</i>, Georgian&nbsp;áƒ–áƒáƒ›áƒ‘áƒ˜&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Greek&nbsp;Î¶ÏŒÎ¼Ï€Î¹, Hebrew&nbsp;×–×•××‘×™&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Hindi&nbsp;à¤œà¥‰à¤®à¥à¤¬à¥€&nbsp;<i>jÅmbÄ«</i>, Igbo&nbsp;<i>zombie</i>, Italian&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Persian&nbsp;Ø²Ø§Ù…Ø¨ÛŒ&nbsp;<i>zÃ¢mbi</i>, Portuguese&nbsp;<i>zombie</i>&nbsp;/&nbsp;<i>zumbi</i>, Russian&nbsp;Ğ·Ğ¾Ğ¼Ğ±Ğ¸&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Somali&nbsp;<i>zombie</i>, Sorani (Kurdish)&nbsp;Ø²Û†Ù…Ø¨ÛŒ&nbsp;<i>zombÃ®</i>, Spanish&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>, Tamil&nbsp;à®¸à¯‡à®¾à®®à¯à®ªà®¿&nbsp;<i>sÅmpi</i>, Turkish&nbsp;<i>zombi</i>. <br><br>A number of the translations substitute a similar concept or kind of monster: the old 1.12 Asturian translation&nbsp;<i>muertu viviente</i>&nbsp;\"living dead\", Belarusian&nbsp;Ğ¼ÑÑ€Ñ†Ğ²ÑĞº&nbsp;\"corpse\", Chinese&nbsp;åƒµå°¸&nbsp;/&nbsp;æ®­å±&nbsp;\"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jiangshi\">jiangshi</a>\", Icelandic&nbsp;<i>uppvakningur</i>&nbsp;\"zombie\" (literally \"one who wakes up\"), Latin&nbsp;<i>resurrectus</i> \"risen again\", Maltese&nbsp;<i>mostru</i>&nbsp;\"monster\", Sicilian&nbsp;<i>mortuvivu</i>&nbsp;\"living dead\",  Yoruba&nbsp;<i>áº¹bá»ra</i>&nbsp;\"<a href=\"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BA%B9b%E1%BB%8Dra\">mythological monster or troll believed to live in forests</a>\".<br><br>In agreement with the majority of the translations, a loanword such as [k]â²â²Ÿâ²™â²¡â²“[/k] is most likely to be widely understood by players.",
