	"color.cyan": {
		"coptic": "â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²Ÿâ²¥ / â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²",
		"date": new Date( "12 Apr 2024" ),
		"english": "Cyan",
		"etym": ["< Greek ÎºÎ±Î»Î»Î¬â²“Î½Î¿Ï‚ \"shifting between blue and green\" [c]lsj|ÎºÎ±Î»Î¬ÏŠÎ½Î¿Ï‚[/c]"],
		"notes": "\"turquoise (attributive)\" [c]cdo|C9276[/c]. This is the only word I've seen attested in Coptic that fits this kind of color. It must be attested in at least four places, because it has the spelling variations [k]â²•â²â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²Ÿâ²¥[/k], [k]â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²[/k], [k]â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²Ÿâ²¥[/k] and [k]â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²“â²›â²‰[/k] [c]cdo|C9270[/c]. At least three of these attestations appear back to back in a passage in <i>The Discourse on the Eighth and Ninth</i> in Nag Hammadi Codex VI:<br><br>[k]â²± â²¡â²[Ï£â²â²£â²‰] â²¡Ï£â²Ï«â²‰ â²™Ì„â²¡[r]item.book.name|Ï«â²±â²±â²™â²‰|true[/r] â²¥â²Ï©Ï¥Ì„ â²â²›â²¥â²§â²â²—â² â²›Ì„<b>â²•â²â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²Ÿâ²¥</b> : â²± â²¡â²Ï£â²â²£â²‰ â²¡â²‰â²‰â²“[r]item.book.name|Ï«â²±â²±â²™â²‰|true[/r] Ï£Ì„Ï£â²‰ â²‰â²¥â²Ï©Ï¥Ì„ â²‰Ï©â²‰â²›â²¥â²§â²â²—â² â²›Ì„<b>â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²Ÿâ²¥</b> Ï©â²›Ì„Ï©â²›Ì„â²¥Ï©â²‰â²‰â²“ â²›Ì„â²¥â²Ï©â²¡â²£â²â²‰â²“Ï£[/k]<br>O my [son], write the language of the [r]item.book.name|book|true[/r] on steles of <b>turquoise</b>. O my son, it is proper to write this [r]item.book.name|book|true[/r] on steles of <b>turquoise</b>, in hieroglyphic characters. (Codex VI, <i>TDotE&N</i> p.61)<br><br>[k]â²•â²± â²›Ì„â²‡â²‰ â²›Ì„â²Ÿâ²©[r]tile.stone.stone.name|â²±â²›â²‰|true[/r] â²›Ì„â²…â²â²—â²â²•â²§â²“â²§â²â²¥ â²™Ì„â²¡â²“â²§â²›Ì„ â²›Ì„â²›Ì„â²¡â²—â²â² â²›Ì„<b>â²•â²â²—â²—â²â²‰â²“â²›â²</b> â²‰Ï¥â²‰ â²›Ì„â²§â²‰â²§â²£â²â²…â²±â²›â²Ÿâ²› â²›Ì„â²…â²¥Ï©â²â²“ â²¡â²£â²â²› â²‰â²§â²¡â²—â²â² â²›Ì„[r]tile.stone.stone.name|â²±â²›â²‰|true[/r] â²›Ì„â²¥â²â²¡â²¡â²‰â²“â²£â²“â²›â²Ÿâ²› Ï©â²›Ì„Ï©â²›Ì„â²¥Ï©â²â²‰â²“ â²›Ì„â²¥â²Ï©â²¡â²£â²â²‰â²“Ï£[/k]<br>And put a square milk-[r]tile.stone.stone.name|stone|true[/r] at the base of the <b>turquoise</b> tablets, and write the name on the azure [r]tile.stone.stone.name|stone|true[/r] tablet in hieroglyphic characters. (ibid, p.62)<br><br>This word is spelled differently every time. This is partially due to the gender of the nouns they modify; [k]â²¥â²§â²â²—â²[/k] \"stele\" is masculine and [k]â²¡â²—â²â²[/k] \"tablet\" is feminine. The [k]-â²—-[/k] and [k]-â²—â²—-[/k] variation is present in Greek as well. I chose [k]-â²—â²—-[/k] only because it is the more common variation.<br><br>~~~<br><br>In Demotic, the word was [d]ğ“…“ğ“†‘4:ğ“¡:Â°ğ“‡‹ğ“²ğ“ŠŒ1[/d]<i>mfky</i> \"turquoise, also imitation turquoise made of colored glass or faience\" [c]cdd_m|82[/c] [c]dpdp|d2413[/c]. It was certainly used both to refer to the material, and as a color word:<br><br><i>ltm á»‰wâ¸—f rt á»‰wâ¸—f n <b>á»‰wn mfky</b></i><br><i>ltm</i> which grows being the <b>color of turquoise</b> (P Carlsberg 230 4+5, x+2/10)<br><br>This word is from Egyptian[h]ğ“…“ğ“†‘ğ“‚“ğ“ğ“ˆ“[/h]<i>mfkêœ£.t</i> \"turquoise\" [c]tla|69410[/c], also used as a color word \"green of plants\" [c]tla|69420[/c]. As far as I know, there is no surviving Coptic descendant.",
		"tags": [ "color", "etym-grk", "vanilla" ]
	},
