		"img": "none",
		"notes": "\"game\" [c]cdo|C9980[/c].<br><br>This is the only word I can find attested for \"game\"; it seems to be used with a negative connotation. For example translations of the Gospel of Philip from Nag Hammadi Codex II have \"trifle\" or \"foolish thing\":<br><br>[k]â²Ï¥â²‰â²“ [...] â²â²¡â²§â²â²£Ï¥ â²‰â²§â²ƒâ²‰ [... â²Ÿâ²©<b>â²¡</b>]<b>â²â²“â²…â²›â²“â²Ÿâ²›</b> â²¡â²‰, â²â²—[â²—â²... â²£Ì„â²•â²â²§â²â²«]â²£â²Ÿâ²›â²‰â²“ â²™Ì„â²¡â²‰â²“â²¡â²‰-[...]â²› â²‰â²§â²™â²›Ì„â²§â²‰â²£â²Ÿ â²›â²™Ì„[â²¡â²â²©â²‰...] â²‰Ï¥Ï£â²â²£Ì„â²•â²â²§â²â²«â²£â²Ÿâ²›â²‰â²“ [... â²]â²©â²± â²›Ì„Ï¥Ï£â²Ÿâ²¥Ï¥ Ï©â²±â²¥ <b>â²¡â²â²“â²…â²›â²“</b>[<b>â²Ÿâ²›</b>... â²‰â²ƒ]â²Ÿâ²— â²‰Ï¥â²¥â²±â²ƒâ²‰.[/k]<br><br>He came [...] to the entirety because [...] it is [a] <b>foolish thing</b>, but [...] despise this [...] the kingdom of [heaven...]. If he despises [...] and looks down on it as a <b>foolish thing</b> [...] he is laughing. (Smith, <i>Valentinian Christianity</i> 283)<br><br>Its usage in Coptic may be limited due to the subject matter of the texts, but in Greek the word is evidently broad enough:<br><br>\"...games with dice, board games, and games of skill played by children or adults, excluding athletic, acrobatic, and theatrical activities, as forexample the Olympic and other contests, gladiatorial combats, or chariot races ... the Greek term <i>paignion</i> ... comprise all these kinds of games.\" (SchÃ¤dler, <i>Games, Greek and Roman</i>)<br><br>Ï€Î±Î¯Î³Î½Î¹Î¿Î½ is also the ancestor of Modern Greek Ï€Î±Î¹Ï‡Î½Î¯Î´Î¹ \"game\" and its derivative Î²Î¹Î½Ï„ÎµÎ¿Ï€Î±Î¹Ï‡Î½Î¯Î´Î¹ \"video game\".<br><br>~~~<br><br>The Demotic word[d]ğ“„‘:ğ“›@ğ“…¡â—³ğ“¤:Â°ğ“‰»:ğ“‚*ğ“›ğ“»:Â°ğ“[/d]<i>á¸¥bêœ¥.t</i> \"game(-board)\" would have been a good fit as well. It is derived from[d]ğ“„‘:ğ“›@ğ“…¡â—³ğ“¤ğ“‰»:ğ“‚*ğ“›ğ“»:Â°[/d]<i>á¸¥bêœ¥</i> \"to play (a game)\" [c]cdd_h2|87[/c] [c]dpdp|d4025[/c] [c]dpdp|d4026[/c]. Neither word survives in Coptic as far as I know.",
