	"tile.tallgrass.name":{
        "coptic": "â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥",
		"date": new Date( "9 April 2024" ),
        "english": "Grass",
		"etym": ["< Greek Ï‡ÏŒÏÏ„Î¿Ï‚ \"feeding-ground, pasture, fodder, provender, green crop\""],
        //"etym": [ "< Demotic[d]ğ“‹´ğ“…“ğ“„§ğ“†°ğ“ª[/d]<i>sm</i> \"herbs\", < Egyptian[h]ğ“‹´ğ“‡ğ“…“ğ“†°ğ“¥[/h]<i>smw</i> \"herbs\" [c]ce|152[/c]" ],
        "notes": "I originally had here [k]<b>â²¥â²“â²™</b>[/k] \"grass, fodder, herbs\" [c]cd|334a[/c] [c]cdo|C3525[/c] [c]ce|152[/c] [c]lambdin|268[/c]. This is a good semantic match, and it is well attested, but it isn't as common of a word in Sahidic as I thought it was. A quick search on the Coptic Scriptorium ANNIS returns zero results.<br><br>Searching through the medical texts, [k]â²¥â²“â²™[/k] is often modified by or modifies other nouns to refer to specific herbs and oils. The most common of these usages is [k]â²›â²‰Ï© â²›Ì„â²¥â²“â²™[/k] \"radish oil\" [c]cdo|C3527[/c] [c]ce|152[/c] [c]sawy|145, 161, 205, 208[/c]. Others include [k]â²¥â²“â²™ â²›Ì„â²Ÿâ²©â²Ÿâ²ŸÏ©â²‰[/k] \"scorpion grass (= <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schenkia_spicata\"><i>Erythraea spicata</i></a>)\" [c]cd|509a[/c] [c]cdo|C5303[/c] [c]ce|223[/c] [c]sawy|204-205[/c] and [k]â²¥â²“â²™ â²›Ì„Ï­â²£â²Ÿâ²Ÿâ²™â²¡â²‰[/k] \"dove herb (= Ï€ÎµÏá¿ÏƒÏ„Î­Ïá¿Î¿Î½, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verbena_officinalis\"><i>Verbena officinalis</i></a>)\" [c]cd|334a[/c] [c]sawy|59, 92[/c]. None of these usages are close in meaning to the grass intended.<br><br>When referring to grass or herbs in the general sense, as occurs throughout the Bible for example, while Bohairic texts do use [k]â²¥â²“â²™[/k] in this way, the Sahidic parallels have the Greek [k]<b>â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥</b>[/k] [c]cdo|C10977[/c] instead. This word is very common; ANNIS search returns 58 uses in 48 documents. For example:<br><br>[k]â²Ï¥â²Ÿâ²©â²‰Ï©â²¥â²Ï©â²›â²‰ â²‰â²§â²£â²‰â²›â²™â²â²Ï£â²‰ â²›â²ŸÏ«â²Ÿâ²© â²‰Ï©â²£â²â²“ â²‰Ï«â²™â²¡â²‰<b>â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥</b>[/k]<br>He commanded the multitudes to sit down on the <b>grass</b> (Matthew 14:19).<br><br>All four gospels include the account of Jesus feeding of the multitudes, of which three of them mention the grass the crowd sat on, and those three all refer to it as [k]â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥[/k] in Sahidic. (Mark 6:39 more specifically calls it [k]â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥ â²‰â²§[r]color.green|â²Ÿâ²©â²‰â²§â²Ÿâ²©â²±â²§|true[/r][/k] \"green grass\".) This is the kind of grass that covers the ground, like in a Minecraft world-- [k]â²¡â²‰â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥ â²‰â²§Ï©â²›Ì„â²§â²¥â²±Ï£â²‰[/k] \"the grass in the field\" (Luke 12:28), in other words.<br><br>I also checked the Bohairic equivalents of all these passages, and every one has [k]â²¥â²“â²™[/k] in the same places where Sahidic has [k]â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥[/k]. Although there are nuances in usage, such as the aforementioned specific herbs and oils, these two words are apparently synonymous. This is not a matter of which word is more correct, but rather which is more typical of the dialect being used, and which a reader familiar with that dialect will more likely understand. So a Sahidic Minecraft translation will use what is typical of Sahidic, [k]â²­â²Ÿâ²£â²§â²Ÿâ²¥[/k], and a Bohairic translation will use [k]â²¥â²“â²™[/k].",
        "tags": [ "block", "etym-grk", "plant", "vanilla" ]
    },
